<hr />
<h2>4 · Explain the Code 📖</h2>
<p>Here is a working gravity-and-jump player, like the one from your lesson. Read it carefully, then answer the questions.</p>
<pre><code class="language-python">GRAVITY = 0.7
JUMP_STRENGTH = -14
velocity_y = 0
on_ground = True

# inside the event loop
if event.key == pygame.K_SPACE and on_ground:
    velocity_y = JUMP_STRENGTH
    on_ground = False

# every frame
velocity_y = velocity_y + GRAVITY
player.y = player.y + velocity_y

if player.y &gt;= HEIGHT - 50:
    player.y = HEIGHT - 50
    velocity_y = 0
    on_ground = True
</code></pre>
<p><strong>What does the line <code>velocity_y = velocity_y + GRAVITY</code> do every frame?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Why does a jump set <code>velocity_y</code> to a <em>negative</em> number instead of a positive one?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Right after a jump, <code>on_ground</code> becomes <code>False</code>. Why is that important?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>What three things happen when <code>player.y &gt;= HEIGHT - 50</code> is true?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>If you deleted the line <code>velocity_y = 0</code> at the bottom, what would go wrong?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

